WebTV Plus features for Game Developers

With the release of Client 2.2 and Etude 1.1, it is possible for third party
developers to create video games for the WebTV Plus Internet receiver. These
games are implemented as Alternate Application ROMs.

The WebTV game development model is similar to the console video game
market. You must enter into a contractual agreement with WebTV Networks in
order to deliver your game to WebTV customers. Terms and conditions vary.
Currently there is no mechanism for billing customers for game usage.

In order to develop a game for WebTV you need the following:

   * A personal computer running Windows 95 / 98 / NT with 64Mb of RAM and
     2Gb of hard disk.
   * A signed NDA with WebTV.
   * A WebTV Plus Internet receiver.
   * A special parallel port cable to connect your WebTV Plus Internet
     receiver to your PC.

The following features are available for game development:

   * The complete source for the WebTV port of the game Doom.
   * For normal games, there is a 512 x 384 x 8-bit-per-pixel
     double-buffered graphics mode.
   * For more adventurous developers, there is a 2D sprite engine with
     hardware rotation and scaling, and 16 bits-per-pixel YUYV graphics.
   * The IR keyboard can have any 4 keys down at once, and has both key down
     and key up events.
   * The audio hardware and software allows real-time 16-bit, 44-kHz, stereo
     mixing.
   * There is a MS-DOS compatable VFAT file system with long file names. (Up
     to 10 Mb of read-only, and 30Mb of read/write disk space available per
     game.)
   * Game logs and crash logs allow valuable information to be collected
     from beta-testers and end-users.
